            <div class="input-wrapper"><span class="prefix">$</span><input type="number" id="growth-eps3" value="" placeholder="optional" step="0.01"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-group">
            <label for="growth-eps4">Year 4 EPS</label>
            <div class="input-wrapper"><span class="prefix">$</span><input type="number" id="growth-eps4" value="" placeholder="optional" step="0.01"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-group">
            <label for="growth-eps5">Year 5 EPS</label>
            <div class="input-wrapper"><span class="prefix">$</span><input type="number" id="growth-eps5" value="" placeholder="optional" step="0.01"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="results-panel">
          <div class="result-box primary-result">
            <span class="calc-result-label">YoY EPS Growth Rate</span>
            <span class="calc-result-value" id="growth-yoy-result">+42.9%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="secondary-results">
            <div class="result-item"><span class="result-label">EPS Change ($)</span><span class="result-value" id="growth-change">+$1.50</span></div>
            <div class="result-item"><span class="result-label">Multi-Year CAGR</span><span class="result-value" id="growth-cagr">—</span></div>
            <div class="result-item"><span class="result-label">Years in CAGR</span><span class="result-value" id="growth-years">—</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- P/E from EPS Calculator -->
    <div class="calculator-card" id="pe-calculator">
      <h2>P/E Ratio from EPS Calculator</h2>
      <p class="calc-desc">Enter a stock price and EPS to compute the price-to-earnings ratio. The EPS auto-fills from the basic EPS calculator above.</p>
      <div class="calc-grid">
        <div class="input-panel">
          <div class="input-group">
            <label for="pe-stock-price">Current Stock Price</label>
            <div class="input-wrapper"><span class="prefix">$</span><input type="number" id="pe-stock-price" value="110" min="0" step="0.01"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-group">
            <label for="pe-eps">Earnings Per Share (EPS)</label>
            <div class="input-wrapper"><span class="prefix">$</span><input type="number" id="pe-eps" value="5.00" min="0.01" step="0.01"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="results-panel">
          <div class="result-box primary-result">
            <span class="calc-result-label">P/E Ratio</span>
            <span class="calc-result-value" id="pe-result">22.0×</span>
          </div>
          <div class="secondary-results">
            <div class="result-item"><span class="result-label">Interpretation</span><span class="result-value" id="pe-interpretation" style="font-size:0.85rem">Fairly valued</span></div>
            <div class="result-item"><span class="result-label">Earnings Yield</span><span class="result-value" id="pe-earnings-yield">4.5%</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Magnificent 7 EPS Chart -->
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>Magnificent 7 — EPS Comparison (2024)</h2>
      <p>Earnings per share vary dramatically among the Magnificent 7 mega-cap tech stocks. META leads with $22.10 EPS, while TSLA trails at $2.50 — a near 9× difference that reflects vastly different profitability profiles.</p>
      <div class="chart-container"><canvas id="mag7Chart"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <!-- S&P 500 EPS Growth Chart -->
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>S&P 500 EPS Growth (2015–2025)</h2>
      <p>S&P 500 earnings per share have grown from roughly $100 in 2015 to an estimated $240 in 2025 — a compound annual growth rate of approximately 8.5%. The COVID dip in 2020 and subsequent recovery are clearly visible.</p>
      <div class="chart-container"><canvas id="sp500EpsChart"></canvas></div>
    </div>

    <!-- What is EPS -->
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>What Is Earnings Per Share (EPS)?</h2>
      <p>Earnings per share is the most widely followed profitability metric on Wall Street. It measures how much net profit a company earns for each outstanding share of common stock. When analysts say a company "beat expectations," they almost always mean it reported EPS above the consensus estimate.</p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <h3>The EPS Formula</h3>
        <code>Basic EPS = (Net Income − Preferred Dividends) ÷ Weighted Average Shares Outstanding</code>
        <p style="margin-top:1rem;font-size:0.9rem">To calculate <strong>diluted EPS</strong>, add potentially dilutive shares to the denominator:<br><code>Diluted EPS = (Net Income − Preferred Dividends) ÷ (Weighted Avg Shares + Net Dilutive Shares)</code></p>
      </div>

      <h3>Why EPS Matters</h3>
      <p>EPS is the foundation of stock valuation. The price-to-earnings (P/E) ratio — the most common valuation metric — is simply the stock price divided by EPS. When EPS grows, the stock price tends to follow (assuming the P/E multiple stays constant). Investors, analysts, and the financial media all obsess over EPS because it directly connects company profitability to share price.</p>

      <h3>EPS and the P/E Ratio</h3>
      <p>The relationship between EPS and stock price is expressed through the P/E ratio: <strong>Stock Price = EPS × P/E Multiple</strong>. A company earning $5 per share with a 20× P/E trades at $100. If EPS grows to $6, the stock rises to $120 — assuming the market maintains the same multiple. This is why EPS growth is the primary driver of long-term stock returns.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Basic vs Diluted EPS -->
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>Basic vs. Diluted EPS — When Diluted Matters More</h2>

      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="col-card positive-card">
          <h3>📊 Basic EPS</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Uses actual shares outstanding</strong> — the weighted average number of common shares during the period.</li>
            <li><strong>Simpler calculation</strong> — straightforward and easy to understand.</li>
            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Companies with minimal stock-based compensation and few convertible securities (traditional industrials, banks, utilities).</li>
            <li><strong>Limitation:</strong> Overstates per-share earnings when significant dilutive securities exist.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-card negative-card">
          <h3>📉 Diluted EPS</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Includes all potential shares</strong> — options, warrants, and convertible bonds increase the denominator.</li>
            <li><strong>Treasury stock method</strong> — assumes options are exercised and proceeds buy back shares at market price.</li>
            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Tech companies with heavy stock-based compensation (the gap between basic and diluted EPS can be 5-15%).</li>
            <li><strong>Always use diluted EPS</strong> when valuing companies with significant equity compensation — basic EPS will mislead you.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- EPS Manipulation Red Flags -->
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>EPS Manipulation Red Flags</h2>
      <p>EPS is a powerful metric, but it can be gamed. Here are the most common ways companies inflate their EPS — and how to spot them.</p>

      <div class="red-flags-grid">
        <div class="flag-card">
          <span class="flag-icon">🔄</span>
          <h4>Share Buybacks Inflating EPS</h4>
          <p>A company can boost EPS simply by buying back shares, reducing the denominator — even if net income is flat or declining. <strong>Red flag:</strong> EPS growth of 15% while net income grew only 3%. Always compare EPS growth to net income growth.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flag-card">
          <span class="flag-icon">🎯</span>
          <h4>One-Time Gains</h4>
          <p>Selling an asset, settling a lawsuit, or recording a tax benefit can produce a one-time EPS spike. <strong>Red flag:</strong> Sudden EPS jump with no corresponding revenue growth. Check if "other income" or "extraordinary items" drove the beat.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flag-card">
          <span class="flag-icon">🚫</span>
          <h4>"Adjusted" or Non-GAAP Exclusions</h4>
          <p>Companies exclude stock-based compensation, restructuring charges, or amortization as "non-recurring" — even when they recur every year. <strong>Red flag:</strong> Non-GAAP EPS is consistently 30-50% higher than GAAP EPS. If the adjustments happen every quarter, they are not one-time.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flag-card">
          <span class="flag-icon">📈</span>
          <h4>Aggressive Revenue Recognition</h4>
          <p>Pulling forward revenue from future periods inflates current-period earnings. <strong>Red flag:</strong> Revenue growing faster than cash flow from operations. Receivables growing faster than revenue. Deferred revenue declining unexpectedly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Key Insights -->
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>5 Key Insights About EPS</h2>
      <div class="insights-list">
        <div class="insight-item">
          <span class="insight-num">1</span>
          <div>
            <h4>EPS drives stock prices more than any other metric</h4>
            <p>Over the long term, stock prices track earnings growth. A company that compounds EPS at 15% annually will see its stock price roughly double every 5 years — even without P/E expansion. This is why growth investors obsess over EPS trajectory.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insight-item">
          <span class="insight-num">2</span>
          <div>
            <h4>Always use diluted EPS for tech stocks</h4>
            <p>Tech companies issue massive amounts of stock-based compensation. Using basic EPS for a company like Tesla or Nvidia overstates per-share profitability by 5-15%. Diluted EPS gives the true economic picture of what each share really earns.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insight-item">
          <span class="insight-num">3</span>
          <div>
            <h4>EPS without context is meaningless</h4>
            <p>An EPS of $10 tells you nothing in isolation. Is the P/E 5× or 50×? Is EPS growing or shrinking? Is it GAAP or adjusted? Always pair EPS with the P/E ratio, growth rate, and quality of earnings analysis to get the full picture.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insight-item">
          <span class="insight-num">4</span>
          <div>
            <h4>Buyback-driven EPS growth is lower quality</h4>
            <p>If a company's EPS grew 12% but net income only grew 2%, the difference came from share buybacks — not from growing the business. While buybacks can create value for shareholders, EPS growth fueled by actual revenue and profit expansion is far more sustainable.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insight-item">
          <span class="insight-num">5</span>
          <div>
            <h4>Consistent EPS growth matters more than absolute EPS</h4>
            <p>Meta's $22 EPS is higher than Nvidia's $2.94, but that doesn't make META the better investment. What matters is the growth trajectory, sustainability, and the price you pay for that EPS. A company growing EPS at 30% CAGR deserves a much higher P/E than one growing at 5%.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item"><summary>What is earnings per share (EPS)?</summary><p>Earnings per share measures the portion of a company's net profit allocated to each outstanding share of common stock. It is calculated as (Net Income − Preferred Dividends) ÷ Weighted Average Shares Outstanding. EPS is the single most widely followed profitability metric and forms the denominator of the P/E ratio.</p></details>
        <details class="faq-item"><summary>How do you calculate diluted EPS?</summary><p>Diluted EPS accounts for all potentially dilutive securities — stock options, convertible bonds, and warrants. The treasury stock method assumes in-the-money options are exercised and proceeds buy back shares at the average market price. Diluted EPS = (Net Income − Preferred Dividends) ÷ (Weighted Average Shares + Net Dilutive Shares).</p></details>
        <details class="faq-item"><summary>What is the difference between basic and diluted EPS?</summary><p>Basic EPS uses only actual shares outstanding, while diluted EPS includes all potentially dilutive securities. Diluted EPS is always less than or equal to basic EPS. A large gap signals heavy stock-based compensation — common in tech. Analysts and investors prefer diluted EPS for valuation.</p></details>
        <details class="faq-item"><summary>How do you calculate EPS growth rate?</summary><p>Year-over-year EPS growth = ((Current EPS − Prior EPS) ÷ |Prior EPS|) × 100. For multi-year growth, use CAGR: ((Ending EPS ÷ Beginning EPS)^(1/n) − 1) × 100. Consistent double-digit EPS growth over 5+ years is a hallmark of high-quality compounders.</p></details>
        <details class="faq-item"><summary>Can EPS be manipulated?</summary><p>Yes. Companies can inflate EPS through share buybacks (reducing the share count), one-time gains, aggressive revenue recognition, or excluding recurring costs as "non-recurring." Always compare GAAP vs. non-GAAP EPS, verify that EPS growth matches net income growth, and confirm earnings with cash flow from operations.</p></details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>

<style is:inline>
